## ⏱️ Complexity Analysis

| Metric | Complexity | Explanation |
|--------|-----------|--------------|
| **Time** | `O(n)` | Single pass through `gain`, O(1) work per element |
| **Space** | `O(1)` | Only two scalar variables (`highest`, `num`) regardless of input size |

This is **optimal** — you cannot solve this problem in better than O(n), since the answer depends on every value in `gain`, and O(1) extra space is the minimum needed to track a running sum and a running max.

---

## 🔑 Key Takeaways

- This is the classic **prefix sum + running maximum** pattern: maintain a running total as you scan, and track the best value seen so far in the same pass.
- Always remember the **implicit starting point** — here, altitude `0` at point 0 — when initializing your "best so far" variable. It's a common source of off-by-one or wrong-initial-value bugs.
- Avoid naming variables after Python built-ins (`max`, `min`, `sum`, `list`, etc.) even when it technically works — it's a small habit that prevents confusing bugs later when you do need the built-in.

